SOC 105
Graded Essay 3

In America, we are trained under the impression that all people of all classes are equal in the eyes of the law and have the same rights. This couldn’t be further from the truth. In reality, one’s class means more than one’s character, and money does so many more things than we realize. In this short essay, I will talk about the differences between what we are taught about class in society and what the readings from class said about the importance of class in the USA.
Growing up, everything was about money. Even if I saw a nickel on the ground, I picked it up because I didn’t want to “Be poor”. Although I was only 6, and overvalued those five cents more than life, I still understood the potential consequences of not having money to pay for things. From the youngest ages, Americans are indoctrinated with the idea about the division between rich and poor, and we are taught that money is the key to happy living. After reading the excerpts, I was further convinced (I already had some kind of idea) that money isn’t everything. While it is important for living, we don’t need to live in an excess of money to be happy.
In the first reading, George Mantsios gives myths and contradicting realities about classism that were really meaningful. The most impactful myth that he gave was that everyone has the equal chance to succeed, given enough work. I liked this because it brought out the obvious stupidity found in so many myths about class and privilege. Not everyone has an equal shot at success, because success in America is based on your education and family, and those contribute to your income. A lot of people don’t get that access to education and strong family, so the majority of them start off at a heavy disadvantage. In the third reading, “From Colonialism to the Coup”, there was a statistic that showed the percentage of the national income that the top 0.1% own. If it was an equal distribution, it would have shown that they have less than 1%, but in 2010, they owned about 10% of the national income. This means that the top 1% must own even more. I did my own research, and it turns out that the top 1% of wealthy Americans owned a shocking 38.5% of the national wealth in 2016. I don’t think I can explain how shocking this is. It’s crazy that there is that much of a disparity in the top 1% from the other 99%. They didn’t teach us that in economics, all I heard was the importance of money for success.
The readings disproved every myth I had ever heard about the equal rights of all classes, and now it is quite apparent to me the importance of class in America. We run on a system dependent on the working class, who are so much lower in the eyes of the law and of other people.

Empirical Puzzle: Separation of Race in Schools
	Race is a modern concept in the eyes of sociologists. It was invented to put one group above another and provide a base for diminishing and demeaning the group it is being used against. Race is based on skin color and tends to be used as a weapon by the ones with lighter or fairer skin. This concept was used to justify slavery from the 17th through the 19th centuries. Now it is used to justify discrimination and separation. In my time, I have witnessed this in every aspect of society, stemming from school to life in the outside world. This brings us to the question of whether racism is still around today. An inquiry based in part on how our ancestors passed down their beliefs, and how they got instilled into people’s brains over time. Yes, the concept of race and racism is printed into everyone’s collective consciousness, though mostly unnoticed, and still plays a major part in everyday critical decisions.
A pattern that seems to occur a lot in the United States is a modern version of segregation. It is not forced segregation, but more of a voluntary separation that happens because of the imprinted concepts and ideologies in our minds. Personally, I have noticed this throughout all aspects of my life, but the most noticeable spot has been in school. When you walk around school, you tend to see everyone cliqued up with the people that they hang out with and most of the time they look the same with similar cultural backgrounds. The collective consciousness is in some way at fault for this way of living because people of differing ethnicities have lived separately for the majority of the United States’ existence. This causes static in the growth of society because without mixing cultures, there will be no advancement towards peace in humanity. 
	This puzzle starts with the sociological concept of race vs ethnicity. The definition of race is the categorization of humans that share the same physical appearance and social qualities. The definition of ethnicity is belonging to a group of people with the same cultural background. People tend to mix these two concepts up or think they are the same thing. The government uses them to categorically divide the nation by sending out the census where you are required to lay claim to a certain race and ethnicity. This makes it possible to put certain cultural groups to be above others in the social aspect. This leads to things such as workplace discrimination and residential segregation.
	This residential segregation tends to divide the youth which as time goes on, grows and keeps people separate. As it says in an article by Think “Racial residential segregation in the United States is the mechanism by which people are sorted into neighborhoods and communities that offer opportunity and deny it.” This tends to mean that people of color in the lower or middle class usually reside in lower-opportunity areas (Think). While middle-class white families are able to live in better neighborhoods. Bringing them more and better opportunities in life. This separates us in many ways as people go to different churches and schools and play sports in different places. This just starts the segregation between races because you make acquaintances and friends that you stick with for the rest of your life. 
 Devah Pager did a study on the hiring process discrimination. It showed many ways how jobs and managers treated and responded to different cultural groups when trying to obtain a job. The people who applied to these jobs all had the same resume, background, and social and communication skills.  The research conducted that white interviewees were twice as likely to have a positive response from the job as a black interviewee and 5% more likely than a Latino interviewee. Similar results happened when people with felonies applied. White felons were 2% more likely to get a positive response than Latinos and 4% more likely than black felons. This is known as subtle discrimination as it is printed into everyone’s collective consciousness to have certain biases and prejudices that often go unnoticed even by the person doing them. It is the result of years of racism trickling down through society over time, making it impossible for anyone to not have a drop of racism in their mind.
	Racism has been a part of the United States since the founding of the country. The concept of the matrix of domination, explains that white supremacy, patriarchy, and capitalism all work together to reinforce each other. From the beginning of the country, the rich white slave owners were building their wealth and power while the black people were being held as slaves, making it impossible to grow wealth and status. The power elite holds the economic power in America and uses this power to exploit the marginalized communities that don’t have access to good economic opportunities. They also held the power to exclude minorities and marginalized groups from getting good access to healthcare and education. 
	My experience with seeing the separation of races throughout society and specifically in school really didn’t make me think much at the time. But these concepts we go over in class opened my eyes to the causes and repercussions of this separation. The concept of race gives people an excuse to degrade another group of people that don’t fit the same physical image and social concepts as them. The way the government uses race and ethnicity to segregate the people of the nation through residency, access to needs like education and healthcare, and workplace discrimination. Systemic racism plays a huge part in many people’s lives, and it is important to find the roots of these problems. Finding the roots is the only way to find a solution.
		The nation is in a split and it goes back to way before any of us were born. The teachings and ideologies of our ancestors have been passed down and imprinted in our minds. This is a case of collective consciousness working against the people of the world. It is the fact that everyone has an underlying way of thinking that is not even noticed by the person thinking most of the time. This is how the youth becomes divided and continues to grow apart as they get older. Concepts like race, and ethnicity, and how sociologists view and research them show us how racism and discrimination run our system here in the United States. The youth of this country need to use this knowledge and listen to the older generation to see where they messed up and how we can fix it. With the way society is now our generation is on a path to finally overcoming racism. Youth nowadays are gaining an awareness of racism that hasn’t been seen yet, on top of the awareness youth today are stepping up and protesting and speaking out on racism. Instead of sitting around and talking about what problems are occurring people are stepping up and fixing the world one problem at a time.

The Effects of Social Media on Self Image

	In any social scene there’s going to be some people that have higher status than others, on social media this is especially relevant and not the most ideal situation. While users gain their popularity and climb to the top of the applications fame, they can be viewed as role models and can inspire people to improve themselves, help others, and do good in the community. Other popular users don’t utilize their reach for good and end up promoting products, goods, and services that will make them money but then the rest of us then feel like we need to be more like them. Oftentimes these promoted items are out of the general population's reach, making us feel as though we won’t be able to become more like them resulting in us feeling down on ourselves. With these users being so easily accessible, these feelings become increasingly common.
	Other pressures of social media don’t even come from the top users, but from common users feeling like they have to present their absolute best self on their own profile for others to see. In Christian Baccarella’s article Social Media? It's Serious! Understanding the Dark Side of Social Media he describes this as “oversharing photos of positive experiences unintentionally causing anxiety among those who live less glamorous”. This includes anywhere from the pressures of posting the perfect picture in order to get the much desired validation from “friends” and “followers”; to scrolling through your own feed and seeing your friends and others posts of that crazy international vacation they’re on, or that fancy restaurant downtown that everyone wants to go to, or some crazy party that you didn’t hear about in time inducing quick feelings of spite and jealousy. With everyone putting on their best fronts for social media it’s easy to come across posts like these and feel down on yourself.
	The American sociologist Charles Cooley’s concept of the “Looking Glass Self” fits perfectly into the role that social media plays in our daily lives. The “Looking Glass Self” is Cooley's concept of how individuals view themselves based on two things; how we directly view ourselves in our own company, and how we perceive others view us. This concept was created in the early 1900’s, prior to any advanced technology, but is still relevant in the fact that through social media, the thought “what will everyone that sees this think of me” goes through any users prior to posting anything. “Presenting one's identity is a central aspect of social media” (Baccarella), although more often than not, the “identity” presented to that social media platform is the one that they want everyone to see; not the most genuine and realistic to that person's actual identity. This is because it is a part of human nature to think about how others will perceive them based on what they are doing, or in this case posting. In fact, prior to posting anything nobody has seen it, so we are basing our view of ourself off of how we think others will perceive what they are about to see. This is exactly what Cooley explains as the second part of how we view ourselves, based on how we believe that others will think of us.
	Having most social media applications typically involve heavy photo-sharing by both peers and celebrities (Burnette), the users with big followings are able to visually show off how they’re living and how they look, usually widely believed to be more attractive with near perfect physique. This combined with being backed by their social reputation, which “can be indicated by the number of followers someone has, the sentiments of the comments expressed about that user, the view and like counts for a user's post, or the status some platforms award to users” (Baccarella), leads to their lifestyle being extremely sought after but near impossible to reach. The photo-heavy social media platforms nowadays lead to general users being more exposed to upward appearance comparisons, which can cause users to develop poorer body image (Burnette). The american philosopher George Mead had a similar concept of self-conception to that of Cooley, but was more general. His concept of “The Self, The I, and The Me” was that “The Me” is how the general society as a whole views someone, “The I” is who that person is and how they act according to this view, and “The Self” is the balance between both “The I” and “The Me”. This is prevalent in social media because with the popular users having such positive comments to a body image post, this can exert influence on young adults’ perceptions of an ideal body and their own body perception (Kim). Making them not want to post pictures of themselves because they think society's view of their “Me” won’t be good compared to those of the popular users.
	The popular users having positive comments to body image posts isn’t always a bad thing though. Because “Social media comments provide users with the ability not only to express their own opinion but also to monitor the other viewers’ collective reactions” (Kim), this allows for the ideal body image to be commonly believed among the social media community, giving some people a goal to work towards as opposed to an image used as comparison. This is more common in users with lower self-discrepancy due to the ideal body being believed to actually be achievable. Users with higher self-discrepancy are more likely to use these ideal body images as means of self comparison/evaluation due to the huge discrepancy and gap they already have (Kim).
	Social media's influence on society and how people view each other is as dominant as ever, which causes many people to put up a front to blend in with the crowd. When viewing these famous social media stars’ profiles it can be easy to get caught up in what to aspire for and end up comparing yourself to them, and everyone does it from time to time. The pressures of showing off your best self on social media will also always be around, but remembering that other peoples profiles are also fronts of their best life can help users to not feel as jealous or self-conscious of themselves when scrolling through their feed. It is and always will be in human nature to care about what others will think of you, but not focusing on this and being confident in yourself will lead to more enjoyable social media experiences.

When beginning to think about class, we usually break it up into three main categories: lower, middle and upper class. Although today, class identity has been stripped away from popular culture. In the readings of Class in America by Mantsios and The Power of Elite by Domhoff, we can separate their ideas of class between what our present collective consciousness is about class rankings in the United States.
The middle class in the United States holds a very small share of the nation's wealth, the gap between the lower class and rich and middle class and rich is larger than it’s ever been. Mantsios states that we do separate ourselves, but we don’t identify as our class ranking. The middle class is so large that associating yourself with 60% percent of the population doesn’t really give one much of an identity they can call their own. Domhoff argues that the social upper class enjoys associating themselves with their status-quo. He believes that through institutions young members of the upper class and those who are new to wealth develop a shared understanding of how to be wealthy. Most, but not all, live expensive and exclusive lifestyles. 
In my own experiences and some of our collective consciousness is that we do not associate ourselves with class. The middle class is so large, that it is difficult to distinguish between what is considered to be rich or poor throughout the United States. I do believe that wealth within the upper class does provide them with more power than people below them. We do not identify ourselves with a class ranking, but the class we live in does have an impact on developing our own identity.

In my life and the lives of others, I have noticed the harmful effects of social media on self-confidence and body image. From friends sharing their insecurities to countless posts advocating unrealistic beauty ideals, the pressure to be perfect is evident. The widespread presence of these images and their impact on people's self-worth presents a puzzle that can be examined through the lens of Wolf's "The Beauty Myth." 
One day, while studying in Randall with my best friend, we decided to take a break and catch up on each other's lives. As we were talking, she pulled out her phone to check her social media. She was scrolling through Instagram when I noticed her expression change, and a sadness washed over her. I asked her what was wrong, but she just shrugged it off, saying it was nothing. I couldn't help but notice that my friend became quieter and more withdrawn after that moment. I knew she had encountered something on social media that had affected her. Finally, after a bit of gentle prodding, she admitted that she had seen photos of influencers promoting an unattainable body image. The images made her feel insecure about her own appearance and fueled her self-doubt. 
It’s really profound how immediate and deep an impact a screen can affect a human being. Something that is so obviously fake, can influence our emotions on a serious level. These algorithms are specifically designed to make you feel a certain way. To garner your attention, and there is no intention within it that is good. On a moral level, there is no reality where this predation is acceptable. 
This instance highlighted how the unrealistic beauty standards perpetuated by social media, as described by Naomi Wolf's "The Beauty Myth," could have immediate and profound effects on individuals like Sarah. Her self-confidence was shaken, and she began questioning her self-worth, wondering if she wasn't attractive enough to be valued by society. 
Naomi Wolf's idea of "The Beauty Myth" suggests that society's beauty standards are an oppressive force, maintained to keep women under control. According to Wolf, these standards are impossible to achieve and always changing, making sure women continuously strive for an ideal they can never truly reach. To better understand this concept, think about the fashion industry's promotion of extremely thin models as the ultimate beauty standard in the 1990s. This ideal was then replaced by a more athletic and toned appearance in the 2000s, leaving women trying to adapt to the new standard.
Using Wolf's concept of "The Beauty Myth," we can now analyze the effects of social media on beauty standards and self-esteem. The constant flood of images on social media platforms, often digitally edited or filtered, strengthens the idea that perfection is achievable. This false belief increases the pressure to fit into these unrealistic standards, leaving people feeling not good enough and always chasing an unattainable goal. Moreover, social media algorithms often keep this cycle going by promoting content that aligns with these beauty ideals, reinforcing the myth's power.
Through the lens of "The Beauty Myth," we can also understand how beauty has become a product on social media. Influencers and celebrities often take advantage of this myth by promoting beauty products and treatments that promise to help people achieve the "perfect" look. This commercialization of beauty creates a culture of consumption that makes money from people's insecurities, further embedding the power of the beauty myth in society.
Additionally, the beauty myth perpetuates harmful gender stereotypes that are detrimental to both women and men. For women, it reinforces the idea that their worth is primarily based on their physical appearance, while for men, it promotes toxic masculinity and the notion that they must adhere to specific body types and appearances. The perpetuation of these stereotypes on social media platforms contributes to a culture that values conformity over individuality and exacerbates the harmful impact of the beauty myth.
By understanding the role that social media plays in maintaining and promoting the beauty myth, we can raise awareness of the issue and encourage individuals to critically evaluate the images and messages they consume. Creating open conversations about the unrealistic standards perpetuated by the media can help empower individuals to challenge these ideals and promote a more inclusive and diverse representation of beauty.
Naomi Wolf's idea of "The Beauty Myth" offers valuable insights into the puzzle of unattainable beauty standards pushed by social media platforms. By understanding how these standards are oppressive and ever-changing, we can start to see the negative effects they have on people's self-esteem and mental well-being. Furthermore, recognizing the commercialization and consumer culture surrounding beauty on social media allows us to question the systems that profit from our insecurities.
The importance of this analysis goes beyond the world of social media, as the beauty myth is deeply rooted in society as a whole. By critically examining and questioning these standards, we can start to break down the oppressive structures that perpetuate them and work towards a more inclusive and empowering definition of beauty. In doing so, we can ultimately create a more just society that celebrates and values diversity in all its forms.
One potential way to challenge the beauty myth is through the promotion of body positivity and self-love. Encouraging individuals to embrace their unique appearances and focus on their personal strengths can help counteract the negative effects of unrealistic beauty standards. By sharing diverse images and stories on social media platforms, we can create a more inclusive online environment that reflects the true variety of human beauty.
Moreover, educating young people about the harmful effects of the beauty myth and the manipulation of images on social media can help build resilience against the pressure to conform to unrealistic standards. Providing tools for critical thinking and media literacy can empower individuals to navigate the digital landscape with a more discerning eye and a greater understanding of the constructed nature of beauty ideals.
Lastly, advocating for greater transparency and responsibility from social media platforms and the advertising industry can help mitigate the harmful impact of the beauty myth. By holding these entities accountable for the content they promote, we can push for a more ethical and inclusive representation of beauty that reflects the diversity of our society.
In summary, applying Naomi Wolf's concept of "The Beauty Myth" to social media allows us to better understand the pressure of unrealistic beauty standards and their impact on individuals' self-esteem and mental health. By acknowledging the oppressive nature of these standards and the role of social media in perpetuating them, we can work towards dismantling the structures that support the beauty myth and create a more inclusive and diverse understanding of beauty. By doing so, we can foster a more equitable society that values and celebrates the uniqueness of every individual.

William Domhoff and Chapter 4 (Equality) of “21 Lessons for the 21st Century” by Yoval Noah Harari, connect the idea that the weakness of the American working class is a potential reason of an enlarged rift between classes. 
Domhoff states that the weakness of the working class began during the Industrial Revolution, when the black/white split between the working class was reinforced, causing conflicts between “skilled” and “unskilled” workers. These workers had no luck organizing themselves through unions, employees had no power unlike their employers who had great influence with politicians. The history of internal division, political frustration and union defeat caused American workers to continue their individualistic ideology. This left the working class with very little social power unless they were a part of the power of elite. Harari shares similar ideology, he believes that the industrial revolution created industrial economies that relied on masses of common workers. The history of the twentieth century revolved to a large extent around the reduction of inequality between classes, races, and genders. Although, the weakness of the working class is the reason that the gap of inequality has grown between social classes. There are signs of growing inequality both between and within societies. Today, the richest 1 percent own half the world’s wealth, and the richest one hundred people together own more than the poorest four billion.
Both Domhoff and Harari could both agree that the working class fuels the power of elite. The 21st century might cause the most unequal societies in history. Just as Americans unify themselves, they begin to separate themselves from each other once again.

Social Media and its influence on Online Social Selves 

Today, social media has strong influences on a person's online social self. Young adults are highly impacted by social networking sites. People can change or update their personalities to create friendships. Social media provides an outlet for people to illustrate themselves by self-presentation. Social media users then manifest their identities to join other communities to increase their sociality. Although, we begin to wonder how someone's online social self may differentiate from their offline social self. Also, how social media effects ourselves and manipulates our personality. Do we create our own identity or are we influenced by social media? Throughout this paper, I will cover multiple concepts that connect the idea that social media plays a crucial role in developing our online social self. 
In class, we studied Cooley and Mead’s argument of social self. Coming to a mutual conclusion that a man's self is the sum total of what he can call his own. Things such as body, clothes, house, friends and family. Man can have multiple social selves, as there are individuals who recognize him and carry a certain image of him in their mind.  We create different social selves because we associate ourselves with multiple groups, and man’s social self is made by the recognition he receives in those groups. We divide up ourselves in all sorts of different selves with reference to our acquaintances, the social process itself is responsible for the appearances of oneself. Therefore, we can argue that social networking sites are partially responsible for the creation of an online social self throughout multiple groups. We being to dive into the social media that allows us to create our online personality. 
Firstly, we will begin discussing how selfies operate as a ubiquitous mode of sociality. (Cambre 2019).  Media and mobile culture often present social media and selfies which then allow active self-creation. We may take selfies for control, to be visible/invisible or just for fun. The practices of “selfie culture”, which consist of posting and receiving selfies, allows us to receive affirmation from others and builds our self-esteem. Overtime replacing old selfies with new ones allows us to create a new social identity. Keeping up with the social stigma makes people believe they must look a certain way over social media in order to develop relationships with new friends and communities. “As such, pictures of the self are understood as the self but also illustrate how personal identity is increasingly rooted in commodifying and objectifying epistemologies. Narrative forms of identity stressing how the self is continuously rewritten and revised within a dialectics of continuity and rupture seem displaced by the selfie” (Cambre 2019). Social media post such as selfies are the beginning of what influences us to keep up with the most present stigma. It is the foundation of developing one's own social self over social media. Next, we consider how our offline self-impacts our online identity.
In the last few years, the internet has become one of the prime places for social interaction among peers. Young adults have a strong need for online socialization, as being offline can sometimes be more difficult. We begin to understand why offline identities influence young people's online interaction, behavioral and cognitive (Helsper 2014). We answer the question, “Does awareness of certain identity aspects influence how teenagers feel about themselves and act in online environments?” (Helsper 2014). We begin by getting greater background knowledge of how adolescents begin to develop their own identity. Interaction and communication are important to develop at this stage in order to build a social network and create a sense of self. Researchers argue a shift as occurred, and now this stage is being done over the internet (Davis 2012). Teenagers have the need to identify with certain social groups and have strong desires to be romantically involved. This begins the idea of belonging influence, and how teenagers think about themselves and who they interact with. “What is clear is that offline personality and identity aspects are used by teens to determine how to present themselves and interact online” (Helsper 2014). 
The Social Identification and Deindividuation (SIDE) is a framework that argues that social identity influences individual's self-perceptions and behaviors according to social norms (Helsper 2014). SIDE builds upon the self-categorization theory, which supposes that recognizing oneself as a member of a social group depends on the awareness of the group as part of the self. Identification within the group therefore leads to behaviors and self-perceptions to conform to group norms. SIDE frameworks have become an explained link between social identity and online interactions. SIDE often researchers about teen identity development in online interactions, or the content of the interaction in relation to one aspect of identity (mostly gender). There have been experiments about how the prominence of gender, ethnicity and generational aspects are manipulated in an online environment. One experiment consisted of 220 students from 15 secondary schools in the United Kingdom, schools were selected based on the ethnic makeup of their student body (Helsper 2014).  All participants were seated behind their own computer, they could not interact with other students unless it was online. “The findings presented here suggest that offline social group norms related to gender and ethnic identities influence how teenagers think about themselves in online interactive contexts and that the way in which they are addressed can change the importance of different identity aspect” (Helsper 2014). This confirms that identities influence how teenagers see themselves and the way they act online. Now that we understand that our offline selves develop our online identities, we now dive deeper into how teenagers develop friendships and communities. 
After discussing self-presentation and our online identities, we can argue that these two things can create friendship development among young adults. The concepts of media richness, perceived functionality and openness lead to friendship development on social media sites such as Instagram (Lee and Borah 2020). Social networking sites have become an outlet for identity expression amongst teenagers. Instagram, an image sharing, and self-presentation application has attracted more than one billion monthly users and is the fastest growing mobile media, social networking sites around the world. From creating personal profiles and posting videos, photos, liking and commenting has created multiple chances for young adults to manifest their identities. This helps strengthen their need for belongingness to their communities. Instagram gives self-expressive opportunities, and this impacts interpersonal dynamics such as developing friendships. Most studies focus on intrinsic factors such as personality traits. “Regarding self-expression, personality trait of openness has been examined under other media contexts and the trait was found to play an influential role” (Lee and Borah 2020). Openness, for example creating blogs and vlogs, has made attention for the explication of self-presentation on Instagram. Goffman’s theory of stage is an analogy in which each individual is merely an actor performing on a stage that represents society. The instant the curtain rises, an actor’s goal is to convince their audience that they are not just playing a character, but rather, that they are the character. The hope is that the audience will react positively to the performance. This is frontstage behavior. When the curtain closes, they are stripped of all falsified identity. Now, the actor is forced to re-enter their reality. They can now engage in backstage behavior, like listening to their favorite song during the commute home. Goffman believed that an individual in society is perfectly represented by an actor on stage. For example, a college student arrives late to class and quietly finds her seat. She is being watched by her peers, or at least she feels like she is, so she quickly attempts to adjust herself to fit in. She usually types notes on her laptop, but when she sees everyone else taking handwritten notes, she quickly decides to pull out her notebook instead. This is an example of frontstage behavior. After class, the student heads back to her dorm to catch up on the notes she missed. There is no longer any external pressure on her to handwrite her notes, so she opens her laptop and begins to type without hesitation. This is an example of backstage behavior. Goffman’s theory of stage outlines the effects of societal pressure concerning an individual’s actions, often guiding the individual to lose sight of their true self in high-pressure settings.
James and Goffman’s theories are underscored by the simple idea that humans have an inherent need to be liked. This desire for reassurance is stronger than a genuine sense of self, causing the self to often become overpowered by superficial selves. Individuals, when found amongst peers, are simply projecting a reflection of their understanding of societal expectations. James’ theory of the social self explains the constant stream of information the brain receives from its surroundings to assimilate a temporary self that has the highest chance of being accepted. Goffman’s theory of the stage builds on the social self, as he claims that one’s genuine self will indeed emerge when one feels as if no one is watching. James would refer to the emergence of one’s genuine self as their pure ego. James’ theory of self and Goffman’s theory of stage are merely extensions of one another, best understood when providing each other context.

The Concept of the Beauty Myth and Othering of Women in Fiction:
 Application in Selected Fictional Media

















	The idea of the beauty myth has been around for centuries in one form or another particularly in fictional media. There has always been an idea of what a “woman” should look, talk, think, and act like that changes from one generation to another. With the goalposts of womanhood changing over the course of time and generations, the pressures surrounding and pushing for conformity have to change with the times.  The emergence of social media and the increasing interconnectedness of people to each other has only served to heighten the societal pressure to adhere to the ideas of what a woman is in different situations. This affects fiction in all forms and provides a blueprint for reality and the people in the real world to follow.

 Gillian Flynn is a popular fiction writer whose works focus on women's relationships with the beauty myths that surround their roles in their worlds and how that affects them and the people around them. I chose to use two of her novels ``Gone Girl” and “Sharp Objects'' as I have a close connection with both pieces. I feel like they demonstrate how the beauty myth is unobtainable in a concrete way and only serves to enforce rules onto women's presence in the world that keep them separate from themselves and their relationships. By changing the goalposts for what a woman is supposed to be, there is no way to “become” a woman and then stay one in the eyes of the collective society. It is a never ending push to conform to constantly changing standards and diffrening situations.

This idea of femininity encompasses every aspect of a person. The film and novel “Gone Girl” , has a monologue where the leading woman, Amy Dunne, is talking about what makes up a “Cool Girl” , the girl that every guy wants as opposed to the person she actually is when she is by herself;  “Cool Girls are above all hot. Hot and understanding. Cool Girls never get angry; they only smile in a chagrined, loving manner and let their men do whatever they want.” This idea encompasses what she looks like, how she talks, how she acts, how she thinks, her relationships with men,  and how she lets people treat her. This is the beauty myth under another name and with a different face but it's the beauty myth all the same. The presence of the beauty myth is so strong that it sinks into fiction and for this specific example, is part of the reason Amy sets the events of the novel into motion. 

Her resentment for the role she feels she has to play, as the Cool Girl her husband wants her to be in spite of his affair and his increasing poor attitude twords her, leads her to frame her husband for her murder as an act of revenge.  Amy even goes as far to tell her husband at the end of the novel that he made her this way and that he wouldn't have wanted her any other way, she goes on to say she wouldn't be capable of loving if she wasn't exactly the way he made her.  This supports the beauty myth as she not only conformed to the “cool girl” her husband wanted; she was also the dutiful wife, the tragic murder victim, the suffering victim when she returned home, and the scheming women her husband is stuck with out of spousal obligation. The beauty myth rewards women that can perform femininity and the roles each situation provides for them but will punish them for the slightest deviation outside the established lines.

To further add to the idea that the beauty myth can be used to push the idea that beauty myth is a consequence in fiction, in “Sharp Objects”, femininity is rewarded and deviance from the norm is punished. The novel is about Camille Preaker, a conventionally attractive journalist, coming back to her hometown to write about a series of murders of children whose teeth are then removed. Her being seen as a “pretty woman” is used by her to get information she needs about the dead girls and their families for her story and she is shamed when her scars, scars she gave herself that “ruin” the idea of what she should look like, are revealed to her romantic interest and her younger half sister, Amma Crellin. Her mother punishes her for having the scars and for her career, as a journalist which is viewed as improper for a woman, in front of Amma, reinforcing the belief to the sister that looks, particularly feminine looks and attitude are everything and are used as bargaining chips in the world. It is shown over the course of the book that all the little girls who were killed were “tomboys”, were known as troublemakers, and all had a history of biting people.

 The climax of the book shows that Camille's younger half sister, Amma Crellin, murdered the girls to punish them for being different and taking more of her mothers attention because of their differences. Amma would then remove the girl's teeth to make a marble floor in her dollhouse that was a replica of her own home. She would murder the girls as punishment for not being “good little girls”, remove their one form of protection, and then use that to play house where Amma was the leading role. Amma used the beauty myth as reasoning for the deaths of these girls, providing severe consequences for inability to conform.

In Gone Girl, the beauty myth is something that Amy comes to resent  because of how much it affects her life and her relationships. In Sharp Objects, Amma uses the idea of how she should look and behave as a girl as a weapon to harm and kill other girls to punish them. Both stories paint the idea of femininity as a looming presence over women, waiting for a mistake or a slip up, and then punishment of some sort will follow. Obviously the real world is not like this, with murderous little girls and scheming housewives waiting in the wings to punish those who act outside the norms, but there is the presence of what you should look, talk, and act like as a woman always at the back of your mind.  This idea has to come from somewhere and fiction is as good a place as any for this to spring from.

Margaret Atwood is quoted as saying “You are a woman with a man inside watching a woman. You are your own voyeur." That there will always be a person watching you inside of you, judging you based on the standards shown to you as you grow up. I used Sharp Objects and Gone Girl for fictional examples as they are pieces of media I found at a time in my life where I was struggling with the idea of the beauty myth. I was raised in a very strict no makeup, no “girly” things household where more masculine traits were praised. I remember being jealous of the other girls my age doing ballet when I did martial arts instead. In high school I envied my best friend going out with her boyfriend on the weekends when I was competing in fighting tournaments. I grew up with no idea how to perform femininity the way I say other girls grow into. My mom never taught me how to do my makeup and my dad never gave my boyfriend the “You hurt my daughter, I hurt you” speech. I felt like I was watching all the girls my age through a glass plane, I could see them but they were totally alien to me. 

Then I found Gone Girl, where the main character resents the way she was brought up into the beauty myth with all her heart. Amy hates the idea that she's supposed to be the perfect wife by other people's standards. This was the first time I had seen media that didn’t endorse the perfect little girl idea of the beauty myth. In the second act of the book Amy goes into hiding by cutting her hair poorly, dying it patchy and uneven, and gaining weight. The novel makes a point in saying she enjoys the rebelling against what she was raised to be. That was so shocking to me at the time. Amy did exactly what you're told not to do from a young age as a girl and not only that, she enjoyed it. As the story goes on, Amy's distaste for other women and their conformity to the beauty myth  is shown and her true colors as a person very comfortable with immoral actions that benefit her are brought to light, but seeing a woman deliberately go against the beauty myth so dramatically showed me that there were other options to how I could inhibit the world without necessarily conforming to femininity to the letter.

The thing that struck me so much about Amy and Camille is that they were allowed to be mean, ugly, and bitter. They resented the people that made them that way and looked out for themselves first. They were not caring or nurturing to anybody but themselves outside of self benefit. They both were so directly opposite to the idea of the loving mother or dutiful girlfriend/wife archetype. They both have goals that directly oppose the leading men of their stories; Amy wants to punish her husband for making her something she doesn’t want to be and Camille wants to find out who the killer is on her own and is at odds with the male detective on the case. At the end of both of their stories, they are both respectively freed from the demands of the idea of femininity by bending the typical roles of women to their own benefit. Amy returns to her husband and is carrying his child, but she makes it clear she is in control of the relationship now and encourages his resentment of her. Camille’s mother is in prison for abusing her and Amma is in prison for murder; freeing Camille from both the bonds of motherhood and daughterhood. This is her breaking away from both roles typically assigned to women in fiction.

Both novels praise and punish conformity to the beauty myth in about equal measure. Camille is praised for being a good sister but punished for being a bad daughter. Both stories paint pictures of complicated ideas around the beauty myth and being a woman at all. Amy and Camille are bitter and angry but they both are shown to have the capacity to care about others. These stories show that the idea of the beauty myth is inherently flawed, it's never that simple but at the same time, a standard that can ever be reached is not simple. It's damning for whoever tries a lifetime of resentment and anger. “Gone Girl” and “Sharp Objects” both end with Amy and Camllie rejecting what was laid out for them and changing it to fit them instead. They changed the narrative of their story and how they are seen in that context. I can only hope more fiction follows this idea that rejecting what “should” happen to a female character bleeds over into real life and helps lessen the stigma around turning your back on what a “woman” should be, think, do, and say.

Do Humans Need Friends to Survive? 
Have you ever thought about the importance of the people in your life? Do you like having lots of friends or just a few quality friends? Do you value human connection in your everyday life? All of these questions establish a human need for contact with others and how that can have an impact on someone’s everyday life. Recognizing that not all human connection is beneficial for you is also important. The way we act around everyone is different and is based upon the setting we are in. This piques the question: are all types of friendships essential for survival, or just some, if any?  
There are many arguments for both sides of this topic. Lots of studies have shown the importance of human interactions, while others have shown that you can survive as an independent. Goffman explores the idea of “self” through an analogy of comparing it to a stage. When there are performers on a stage, each of them has a role they play. They all understand their roles and contribute something to the storyline. He believes that depending on who you are with, you will act a certain way. Essentially, each interaction we have is compared to acting or a “show” we are putting on for an “audience.” The use of “backstage” is where someone may “prepare” for a “performance.” This is the analogy he uses to explain how someone may prepare their personality to match how they feel they should act with specific people. This could be based on how the person thinks others think they should act, or what the person has concluded on how they should act based on group or friendship dynamics they have observed. When comparing the self to a stage, it almost makes it sound as though all of our interactions are ingenuine. This leads to the part of Goffman’s theory that says that we are never truly ourselves unless we are alone. 
That is one side of Goffman’s theory which would make it seem like the people around you do not have any impact on your sense of “self.” However, because you act a certain way in front of others, they are in turn impacting your personality. As humans, we choose how to act in different scenarios based on how we feel as though we should act, not necessarily how we want to act. Awkwardness can occur if someone does not recognize their “role” in a certain group of people. In other words, if you act differently than normal in a situation, it may cause people to be confused or uncomfortable. We all have defined personalities based upon our environment and surroundings. Because making connections with people is important to our ability to navigate the world, friendships and relationships are essential to our survival.  
Personally, I feel as though I have many roles in each of my friend groups. While I feel as though I am being “myself” when I am with each of my close friends, I can see some differences in how I act. It is impossible to act the same way in all settings. I feed off my friends' energies and not all of them have the same energy. It is also based on what “roles” need to be filled in each setting or friendship dynamic. For example, I find myself being quieter and observant in some groups, while in other groups I am more outgoing and energetic. Even though I feel comfortable with all of these friends, I have noticed my role in each group leading me to act a certain way. They are all versions of myself that I have modified slightly to fit the energy of who I am with. Being able to fit a “role” in each setting of your life is a skill that humans must learn to be successful.  
I had never thought about this concept much before learning about how we are never truly ourselves unless we are alone. When we are alone, there is no judgment, no rules, and no outside influences causing us to want to act one way or another. There is no one to react to, therefore, you are completely and utterly “yourself.” No one but yourself can see what is going through your mind or what you are thinking and understand it with the full complexities you can. While this is the true reflection of “ourselves,” it is not realistic to be able to act this way in front of others. Finding people who make you feel as close to this version of yourself as possible is the best way to measure a friendship.  
Reflecting back on the question about if you need friends to survive or not, I would have never said that you do not need friends to survive. Friends have always been something I value and feel is a necessity in my life. Without human interaction and genuine connection, I feel alone and like I am lacking something. I believe it is part of my personality to surround myself with others and feed off their energies. While this is technically altering my sense of “self,” I do not see it as a negative thing. I see it more as an opportunity to expand my thoughts and gain new opinions and views on topics I might not have seen differently otherwise.

According to the reading from Maryanski and Turner, The Neurology of Religion, adolescent apes would leave their units after puberty, which then placed them with apes that they did not know. No bonds were formed between these apes, leaving them to be more independent. So, how did we go from having low sociality to forming family units with strong bonds? The formation of language made it nearly impossible to not be able to connect to others, as it allowed us to communicate with anyone who spoke the same language as us. In order to find a job, you need good social skills to be able to form bonds with employers and get them to hire you. These skills stem from social interactions that take place in our everyday lives. This is a key reason why having friends surrounding you that you feel comfortable with is beneficial. If you are constantly around those that support you, and you feel most closely to your true “self,” these relationships will be beneficial to you.

You can learn from each version of “you” and apply the reactions you get from your “audiences” to other settings and situations. Having friends and forming connections with people is key to our ability to navigate society and the world. Without bonds, we are just existing as an individual. The Significance of Religon
I thought that temple was extremely boring when I started going. Other than the oneg, which is the part after the service where you get free food, I saw no good reason to be there. It felt like I was just going to sit and listen to someone talk in a different language for an hour and a half. As I kept going, it did not get any more fun, but I did start to observe how everyone that attended seemed very content, and everybody got along with each other quite well. This is the first time I had seen such a large community of people united under a set of moral beliefs that were designed to improve the lives of everyone they touched.
After attending weekly services for a while, the idea of becoming a Bar Mitzvah was introduced to me. I decided I would do it. Mainly, I was interested in the afterparty and the gifts that would come my way as a result. Once I committed to my decision, I started attending Hebrew school on Thursdays and Sunday school on, well, Sundays. Learning Hebrew was the first part of Judaism up to that point that I truly enjoyed. It was fun learning how to read a mysterious-looking language, and there were other kids my age there with me going through the same thing. In Sunday school, I sat with the same kids and learned about the history and principles of the religion. I started to get to know many of the people that I had seen at services and build solid relationships.
 Once I had gotten into this routine of Hebrew school on Thursday, service on Friday, and Sunday school on Sunday, things began to get a little more intense. I began to meet with the Rabbi in my free time. I would go into her office and we would sit for an hour each session and study prayers and readings in Hebrew to prepare for my event. Becoming a Bar Mitzvah almost felt like a job at this point. I remember the Rabbi getting upset with me one time because I was reading the English transliteration of the prayer instead of the Hebrew. I was becoming tired of all the hard work.
Of course, even more work came on top of this. I was told I needed to complete a Bar Mitzvah project, which is essentially a social action project that encourages students to combine their talents and hobbies with an act of community service. I have played piano for many years, so I decided to play for senior citizens at retirement homes. I figured that this would serve the community well since many people living in these homes did not have the option to go out to events or see live music. While this was a fun thing to do and it felt good to make people happy, it was even more work that I had to do apart from school and other extracurriculars.
There was a final aspect of my studying on top of everything else. This was a Hebrew tutor, who helped me learn the prayers I had to learn in between my meeting times with the Rabbi. I knew my tutor personally and we got along very well, so this was also a good time, but again, it was more work that I had to do in preparation for what was once just an idea. It was at this point that I began to ask myself what the point of this was. Who was I doing it for? It was not for my parents, my friends, or my teachers. I never answered this question for myself until months later.
Emile Durkheim, a French sociologist, explained the idea of the collective consciousness and collective representations. The collective consciousness is the shared values, beliefs, and viewpoints of a group. A collective representation is something that represents the common beliefs and ideals of a society. For example, a collective representation from American society would be the American Flag. The flag is for all Americans and symbolizes the common American belief system and dream. Rather than being individual people leading completely separate lives and completely forming our own beliefs, the collective consciousness gives us an opportunity to have a group to share knowledge with.
This is what I realized once I reflected on my experience of becoming a Bar Mitzvah. All of the things I had done to work towards a seemingly pointless goal had done something bigger than I could have imagined. It introduced me to a new community of people to share values and beliefs with. I had not been indoctrinated into a belief system, I had been welcomed into a community. I understood that it was actually preparing me to decide to what extent religious values shared by my community would affect and direct my later life, and realized that decisions I make regarding my involvement and participation in the community are fully voluntary, and should come from a place of genuine care.
Once I truly considered these things, everything that had once seemed like a job started to become parts of a whole. The connection to all of these people and ideas that I made through my work bound me to my faith. I now carry the values and lessons I have learned with me and allow them to influence my life and decisions in positive ways. Being a Jew means being part of a unique collective consciousness. A Bar Mitzvah is more than just the rote memorization of various prayers and readings, it is a celebration of an individual taking their place in the community.
In conclusion, the true meaning of religion took me a while to understand. From attending temple, to Hebrew school, to Sunday school, to studying prayers and readings, I am grateful for the community that I have become a part of, even if I did not understand what was happening in the moment. I am very close with the people that I got to know through my experiences. Although I only have experience with one religion, I can extrapolate that all religions and belief systems have rituals that may not be understood by outsiders. However, these rituals serve a purpose in bringing a certain group of people together under shared values. It goes even further than religion. This system of shared values happens with entire countries. Being a part of the collective consciousness provides meaning in one’s life.

For decades, scholars have debated the importance of Gregory Mantsios’ and Max Weber’s ideas in sociology. On one hand, Gregory Mantsios in his article Class in America reveals how one’s social class influences their experiences and opportunities in life. On the other hand, in George Ritzer’s monograph The McDonaldization of Society, Ritzer describes Max Weber’s ideas of rationalization as a process where the world, especially bureaucracies, becomes based on efficiency, predictability, calculability, and control. Although these writings discuss different conversations, Mantsios and Weber’s ideas can be synthesized to understand funerary services in America. Therefore, the purpose of this paper is to evaluate how Mantsios’ idea of class and Weber’s idea of rationalization relate to understanding why Americans choose cremation over other funerary services.
	In Mantsios’ article Class in America, he debunked four myths about the American lifestyle: that America is classless, that America is a middle-class nation, that all Americans are getting richer, and that everyone has an equal chance to succeed. Mantsios exposed the falsity of these myths by revealing the lives of three individuals, Harold S. Browning, Bob Farrel, and Cheryl Mitchell, who are all considered middle-class in America. In examining the different lives of these individuals, he revealed that there existed large economic disparities between each of the individuals from the moment they were born that persisted throughout their lives, shaping their experiences and opportunities. Thereby, Mantsios exposed seven realities to American life. To summarize these realities, Mantsios underlines how there are extreme differences in the economic standing of American citizens as the middle class owns a small percentage of the nation's wealth. This disparity affects Americans’ lifestyles, educational opportunities, chance for survival, and success. 
	An example of where this economic disparity affects American lifestyles is when an American is selecting a funerary service for themselves or their loved ones. Relating to Mantsios’ myths and realities of the American social classes, Mantsios exposes how although the United States is not a country of equal opportunity, Americans still embrace the American dream, which he represented through the myths of American social class. Pertaining to funeral services, there exists a myth about funeral services, which can be showcased in American movies. Once a character dies in a movie, they are depicted lying in an open casket with guests and family lined up in front of the casket weeping and dressed in all black. In reality, most Americans do not hold funerals as 59% of Americans who died in 2022 were cremated according to the Cremation Association of North America (“Industry Statistical Information”). Around 41% of those Americans chose to do a direct cremation (“What the Latest Stats”), which is when an individual is cremated without a memorial service, making it the most cost-effective funerary service. Furthermore, this cremation rate is expected to reach 80% by 2045. This increase in cremation rates is largely due to America's inability to afford funerals. However, other reasons come into play for some Americans, such as environmental concerns about casket burials or preference (“U.S. Cremation Rate”). A survey of 1,500 Americans run by Anthony Martin in 2021 found that “73% of respondents don't have enough money set aside to cover the cost of the average funeral” (Martin). In regards to Mantsios’ ideas of class and economic differences in America, these statistics about cremation rates reveal that most Americans do not have the opportunity to have an open casket funeral or memorial service to celebrate the death of their loved ones. Thereby, the myth of the American dream depicted in movies of grandiose funeral services is debunked by the reality that most Americans cannot afford it. As Mantsios states, Americans' economic disparity is increasing and their wealth is largely dependent on the social class they are born into. This helps to highlight why there is an expected increase in dead cremated in forthcoming years. Ultimately, Mantsios’ ideas of economic disparity between social classes in America can be observed through American's choice of funerary services as most Americans are cremated because it is the least costly funerary service.
	Furthermore, Mantsios’ ideas of economic disparity between social classes in funerary services can be further observed by its relation to Weber’s idea of rationalization. In Ritzer’s monograph The McDonaldization of Society, he describes Weber’s idea of rationalization as the shift in how institutions are built, focussing on efficiency, predictability, calculability, and control, which is done in bureaucracies and Ritzer’s McDonaldization. This shift from pre-modern institutions to modern institutions changes the focus of the institutions from acting out of social meaning to acting out of social purpose. Institutions that act out of social meaning prioritize a symbolic shift and collective understandings, such as transformative baptism in churches to represent religious values. On the other hand, institutions that act out of social purpose prioritize accomplishing a purposeful, collective task, such as exchanging money to purchase goods in banks. This shift in rationalization gets rid of spontaneous interactions; replaces traditions, values, and emotions; and causes individuals, such as consumers and employees to be allowed few choices to their means to an end. These effects of rationalization are often dehumanizing for people affected by it, expressing Weber’s idea of the “iron cage.” 
	As highlighted above in funerary services, cremation is the most cost-effective funerary service. This is because the process of cremation exhibits the characteristics of Weber’s rationalization: efficiency, predictability, calculability, and control. Cremation is an efficient process because it takes between an hour and a half to two hours for a body to get cremated while funeral service takes long hours of planning and executing; cremation is predictable as the outcome, receiving a loved one’s ashes, is guaranteed; cremation is calculable as the service is relatively cheap with a relatively constant cost everywhere unless an individual wants a memorial service with the cremation, which increases the cost; and cremation is controlled as it primarily only needs a cremation chamber to conduct and is primarily the only choice for most Americans as the only affordable option. Although the cremation process is efficient, predictable, calculable, and controlled, it faces the problems of dehumanization explained in Weber’s idea of the iron cage. As most Americans get cremated without a memorial service, the tradition of a funeral, the value of celebrating a person’s death, and the emotions of grief and acceptance that result from traditional funerary services have to be experienced in different manners, which result from the cremation being the only means to an end for most Americans. All in all, cremation exhibits the characteristics of rationalization through its efficiency, predictability, calculability, and control, which in turn causes it to become an iron cage as it is the only affordable option for most Americans. 
	Ultimately, Mantsios’ ideas of social class in America and Weber’s ideas of rationalization can be synthesized to understand why most Americans choose cremation over other funerary services. This is due to the fact that cremation is the only affordable or cost-effective funerary service because it exhibits the characteristics of Weber’s rationalization, which in turn becomes the only option for most Americans because of the economic disparity between social classes in America as explained by Mantsios. It is important to understand this connection between Mantsios’ and Weber’s ideas because it underlines the dehumanizing nature of cremation when Americans cannot afford the expected funeral service depicted in movies, expressing the American dream or myth of funerary services.

Any aspirations that a woman has will be ignored or negatively received and will not be reciprocated by men. A woman’s determination and ambition is considered to be a handicap. The problem with that idea is women were not really made to be controlled. Women are free thinkers with brilliant ideas. Beauvoir talks about how men will tell her “You think such and such a thing because you’re a woman” and the only reply she can think of is “I think it because it is true.”  This is an example of men separating themselves from women and classifying them as “other”. Women were brought in as teachers not just because it was considered a lesser field, but because they put affection over reason. This is very important when dealing with developing minds because children need to be nurtured in order to learn and grow properly. And so, the feminization of teaching developed and prospered. Women dominating the education field seems to imply that women are in fact superior to men at teaching. But if women are “other” how can they be better than men at something?

Women understand the fear of not being believed and believe in each other. The female gender has always come together and fight for what is just for them, whether it’s the right to vote or the #MeToo movement.

That men are the ultimate decision makers in women's lives. But with what they have been given they have redefined and improved. 	To be a woman is to be “other”, but to be a woman is not to be an outcast. Women understand each other because they share the same experiences. Goffman states, “A correctly staged and performed scene leads the audience to impute a self to a performed character, but in this imputation—this self—is a product of a scene that comes off, and is not a cause of it.” Goffman uses this evidence to elaborate on how the self that others see is more or less the product of an act. He goes on to mention that the way we conduct ourselves in front of others is purely for the conformity of those others. The stage creates a movement that can be discredited as easily as it can be credited. This is in pure contrast to the way we live, think, and breathe. We are one, singular, living being. Afterall, it would take a thorough analysis of how you are seen in order to act properly. Let’s say, for example, you go to your significant other’s house for a dinner, and the father is constantly looking at you with furrowed eyebrows. Through the experiment, it was found that there are different discrimination mechanisms used by employers. The first mechanism is categorical exclusions which is when someone is not hired because of their race. The next is shifting standards which require a more intense interview based on someone’s race.
