The Neurology of Religion: Effects of Religion on Society
	As long as homo sapiens has been walking, religion has been a huge part of motivation, interaction, and wellbeing. A lot of research has been done as to why people believe what they believe, and the validity of religious belief comes into question each time this is studied. Does religion have an impact on individuals? Does religion impact our interactions with others? While these can’t be answered definitively, there are strong cases from each side of the argument. This paper will primarily address the major effects of religion, both positive and negative, on individuals and societal interactions and the importance of religion or lack thereof in society. 
	The research studied in class by Maryanski and Turner about the neurology of religion intrigued me, and as a psychology and religion double major, I couldn’t help but become more and more fascinated by this concept the more I thought about it. As a religious person who is part of a religious community, I was told that it was a bad idea to research something that may argue against what I believe. But here I am doing it anyways, because how can I believe something without knowing the scientific processes of why I believe it, and why would I refuse to look at it from both sides? As I got further into this research, I saw that many sociologists and psychologists had contributed, as well as many renowned theologians. The contributions from both sides produced a well-rounded perspective that can help anybody realize that there are advantages and disadvantages to religion in a society that is rapidly turning away from it. Maryanski and Turner define the sociological perspective of religion as “More than just the propensity to behave in a religious manner. Religion is, at one and the same time, a neurological, behavioral, and organizational process (Maryanski and Turner, 2018). 
	The first question we must ask to see how religion impacts society is this: what are the effects of religious belief on individual wellbeing? Research from Christopher Ellison of Duke University suggests that religion enhances wellbeing in four ways. The first way that religion enhances wellbeing is through social integration and support. Humans have a longing for interaction with one another through various ways and being a part of a religious community helps satisfy this. The second way that religion enhances wellbeing is through the establishment of personal relationships with a divine other. This allows people to feel like they are specially made for a purpose, rather than a random result of evolutionary processes. The third way is through the provision of systems of meaning and existential processes, and like the second reason, this helps believers know that they have a purpose, and that humans exist for a reason greater than anyone can comprehend. The fourth way that religion enhances wellbeing is through the promotion of more specific patterns of religious organization and personal lifestyle (Ellison, 1991). Tying into Maryanski and Turner’s definition of religion, Ellison conducted a study on how religion affects individual wellbeing. He asked random individuals to rate from one (low) to eight (high) their satisfaction with community life, nonworking activities or hobbies, family life, friendships, and health or physical condition. Those five categories are what Ellison says comprise “overall wellbeing”. The study resulted in substantial evidence of a positive influence of strong religious faith on higher life satisfaction, greater personal happiness, and fewer negative psychosocial consequences of traumatic life events. The study also showed that religious individuals who were affiliated with a specific sect or denomination reported higher life satisfaction than their unaffiliated counterparts. This first study shows that religion has a positive effect on overall wellbeing of individuals, and that life satisfaction has a positive correlation to the strength of one’s faith.
	The second question we must ask on how religion impacts society is this: how do religious communities interact with other communities, both religious and nonreligious? Similar to ethnocentrism, humans are drawn to those who share experiences, beliefs, and values, and religion helps unite them in that. However, while religion has a positive impact on the life satisfaction and general wellbeing of members of one group, groups often clash against one another because of various differences in belief or conflict of interests. One of the most notable examples of this is the Crusades. Early in the Second Millennium AD, Christians were encouraged to take up arms for what they believe and destroy all people who are nonbelievers. Another example is Islamic Jihad. While neither religion’s text calls for violence against others, misinterpretation of sacred text and fear of “the other” inspires members of religious communities to fight against other groups for political power or superiority. While members of religious groups interact well in smaller groups with members of other religions, the people in power and religious scholars tend not to associate with people who believe other things. The superiority complex of religious institutions is fascinating to me, that a group can believe that they have been ordained by their god to run the world. This makes religion sound like a perfect thing to create to generate income and gain support from people.
	While some religions and sects don’t get along, many religions, namely Buddhism and other Asian religions, are encouraged to spread peace and love to everyone. Some sects of Christianity, like Presbyterians and Methodists, base the foundation of their theology not in conversion of others, but through the spread of their message through showing love to others, like the famous Christian hymn “They Will Know We Are Christians By Our Love”. The positive interactions between religious groups have led to the formation of so many awesome organizations and communities. In my hometown of Raleigh, the Interfaith Food Shuttle is run by people of all religious backgrounds and served to everyone who needs it. My father, who is a Presbyterian minister, is good friends with an Imam, a Rabbi, and a Bhikkhuni. Every American holiday, they organize a service for upwards of five hundred people to celebrate and give thanks for each other and the holiday. We have inter-faith Thanksgiving service, inter-faith Memorial Day service, and inter-faith Independence Day service every year, and this is the pinnacle of religious cooperation and respect. My family celebrates Passover with the Rabbi’s family, and his family celebrates Christmas eve with mine. To say that religious groups cannot have positive interactions would be an absolute lie, because the key to interaction is open-mindedness.
Using the answer to the previous two questions, we are able to get a better understanding of how religion impacts society. Because religion has been shown to increase individual life satisfaction and overall wellbeing, religion impacts the individual positively. Because of heightened religious tension, individuals find it more difficult to have positive interactions with people of other religious groups, but it isn’t hard if one keeps an open mind. Religion would have the best impact on society as a whole if everyone was a member of the same religious community, but that will never be the case. It is hard for many religions to admit that other people have valid reasons for believing what they do, and I think this is because of their own religious insecurity. While I think that it is very beneficial to practice religion for social and individual wellbeing, I find it problematic that there is no evidence to prove the validity of religion, it is all based on tradition. Religion keeps members under control by both fear and mercy, that they can mess up and be forgiven, but if they mess up too badly, they may be struck down by their heavenly figure (Köhrsen, 2012). Another problem with religion is that it just came out of nowhere one day. A person can get a lot of support if they claim that they were ordained by the gods, and many people have taken advantage of that for political power. According to Jaco Beyer, in the case of South Africa, religion and politics have a long history of reciprocal collaboration and/or disagreement (Beyer, 2015). From the earliest societies to present day, religion has had influence on politics. Beyer says that the sacred is present in social institutions, laws are divine commandments, social classes are arranged hierarchically as determined by divine order, education is religious, economic behavior is regulated by the sacred, government is sacral, and that religion and government is an integrated system (Beyer, 2015). A lot of this was seen in colonization, and in Beyer’s case, it was seen in both South Africa and Japan. Even nonreligious sociologists and psychologists seem to agree religion, when used correctly, is a vital part of society. 
Because it answers difficult questions regarding life, death, struggles, and other topics, people tend to accept religious belief as truth and follow the other commandments and values of the given religion. Without religion, the world would be full of unmotivated people who are just waiting for death, knowing that life means nothing. Religion, when used incorrectly, has started the worst wars in history-- most wars have been the result of some kind of religious dispute that got out of hand, and this is part of what led Marx to say, “Religion is the opiate of the people.” While Marx argued that religion keeps people sedated and addicted, not even realizing how harmful it is, other people like Jens Köhrsen argued that religion is what enables people to do so many great things, such as giving to the poor, volunteering time to others, and caring about other people (Köhrsen, 2012). As I said earlier, when religion is used correctly, it is a beautiful piece of humanity that has many positive impacts on society. However, when it is used for political power or economic influence, its impact on society becomes negative. Religion is vital to a functioning society, and this can be seen in all of the ways I spoke about: Individual wellbeing, group interaction, and positive societal impact.
